    <title>Combined summary - A Post Quantum Migration Proposal</title>
    <updated>2025-09-22T10:52:41.063051+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/CAEM=y+Wr4g+kcZpjSUEVay_NCdZcwGSEHcC6W9PcjpibYwd-sA@mail.gmail.com/T/#m376871ab5341f27343e4e85b66d86ca373a5b857" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2025-09-15 16:24:00+00:00</published>
    <summary>The Bitcoin community is currently grappling with how to respond to the potential threat of quantum computing, which could compromise the security of the blockchain by making it feasible to break the cryptographic algorithms that protect Bitcoin wallets and transactions. A series of emails from the Bitcoin Development Mailing List has revealed a detailed discussion among developers, researchers, and enthusiasts on how to best prepare for and mitigate this existential risk.
One proposed solution involves a phased approach to transition Bitcoin to post-quantum cryptography (PQC) before such quantum computers become a reality. This plan includes several phases: initially disallowing transactions to quantum-vulnerable addresses to encourage migration to PQC addresses, followed by invalidating spends from quantum-vulnerable outputs, and potentially introducing a way to recover legacy UTXOs through zero-knowledge proofs or other means.
The motivation behind these proposals is to secure the value of the Bitcoin UTXO set and minimize the incentives for quantum attacks. The introduction of quantum-resistant scripts and address types aims to hasten the adoption of new, safer protocols while providing a clear timeline for the ecosystem to upgrade. This preemptive action seeks to avoid the catastrophic scenario where quantum attackers could covertly compute private keys and steal Bitcoin without immediate detection.
Critics of these measures raise concerns about the ethical implications of forcibly freezing or modifying coins without user consent, potentially setting a dangerous precedent for future interventions in the blockchain. They argue for an opt-in approach to upgrades, emphasizing personal responsibility and the importance of not undermining fundamental principles like user sovereignty and network conservatism for the sake of perceived threats.
Despite these disagreements, there is a consensus on the urgency of developing and implementing quantum-resistant technologies to protect Bitcoin. The debate centers on the most ethical and effective ways to achieve this without compromising the decentralized and open nature of the network. As the threat of quantum computing becomes more tangible, the Bitcoin community continues to explore solutions that balance security, usability, and adherence to its core values.</summary>
